    3.
        In the Torah, the prophet Ibrahim is described as being willing to sacrifice his son Ishmael because Allah commanded it. However, Allah stopped him before he could do so. Modern Muslims commemorate this by sacrificing a sheep during Id to show their dedication to God.

        Another way Muslims may celebrate Id-ul-Adha is by praying. Muslims may do this to reflect on their own obediance (or lack thereof) of Allah's command, contrasting with Ibrahim.
    4.
        One reason why Muslims give Zakah is because it is commanded in the five pillars. Muslims are obliged to obey the five pillars of islam, which are fundamental to the faith. So, Muslims must give Zakah.

        Another reason why Muslims give Zakah is because it is said in the Qu'ran to be compassionate towards the disadvantaged, and because it is taught similarly that Muslims have a duty to reduce suffering. Hence, Muslims will give Zakah in order to reduce the suffering of those in need.
